text:
Guard well thy soul, a treasure most supreme,  
Shaped for the taste of heaven’s boundless might,  
Untouched by guilt, where vice shall never gleam,  
By grace of God inclined to virtue’s light.  
Shield it with care, lest through neglect’s cruel chain  
It fall and drink of everlasting pain.  

Tend to thy flesh, yet for thy soul’s command;  
Let modest fare sustain, let pride be slain;  
Clothe with due grace, no gaudy raiment grand;  
Let wisdom flourish, ignorance disdain.  
Feed, clothe, and care, but balance wisely both,  
That neither flesh nor soul may suffer growth.  

Seek of the world what keeps thy body whole,  
Yet twist no wit toward paths of wrongful gain;  
Oppress no weak, let justice guide thy role;  
To debts unpaid, let no delay remain.  
Spend of thy wealth in measure, not in pride,  
And aid the poor whose needs thou canst provide.  

Cherish thy soul, thy steadfast, guiding flame;  
Guard well thy flesh, yet for thy soul’s delight;  
Respect the world, but virtue’s rule proclaim;  
Let all thou carest lean toward the just and right.  
Thus live, that when thy earthly care is done,  
Thy soul may bask in heaven’s eternal sun.

Nurture your soul, that treasure of divine might,  
Crafted to sip from the chalice of the heavens,  
Free from guilt’s heavy chains, disdainful of vice,  
Ready, by the grace of gods, to dance toward virtue.  
Guard it fiercely, lest your reckless journey  
Plunge it into the abyss of eternal agony.  

Tend to your body, yes, but let your soul lead;  
Slice away the excess, let sustenance be pure;  
Conquer pride with garments that don’t enslave,  
Seek wisdom’s treasure, shun ignorance's cruel grip.  
Feed and clothe the flesh, but do not let them devour  
The essence of both soul and body in their hunger.  

Care for this world, let your body thrive;  
Do not twist your mind in pursuit of shadowy gains;  
Do not crush the weak with unjust might;  
Pay your dues without delay, let justice reign.  
Spend wisely, with an eye on those in need,  
And remember, in all, the heart of compassion.  

Cherish your soul, your steadfast anchor;  
Honor your body for your soul’s delight;  
Tend to this world, a cradle for your flesh;  
But care, oh care, so that virtue shines bright.  
Care in such a way that you can be assured:  
Let not your cares bar you from heaven’s bliss.

My true love holds my heart, as I hold his;  
A fair exchange, in trust and balance given.  
I treasure his, and mine he does not miss;  
No truer pact has ever been so driven.  

His heart in me binds us as one complete;  
My heart in him directs his thoughts and ways.  
He loves my heart, once his, a bond replete;  
I guard his heart, in me it safely stays.  

His heart was struck when first my gaze took aim;  
My heart was pierced by his, in shared despair.  
The pain from me to him returned the same,  
And in this mutual wound, our joy lay bare.  

Thus, through this trade, our perfect union is:  
My true love holds my heart, as I hold his.
